image.altText: Geelong mum Sheridan Digby standing outside in sunlight, looking off to the side with a neutral expression

props.synopsis: Sheridan Digby had hoped a 2019 remedial massage would help fix her sore neck. Instead, she says it caused her to suffer a stroke. The Geelong mum is now suing the masseuse and medical clinic, arguing they are liable for her injuries.

title.children: Sheridan suffered a stroke after a massage. Now she's suing the masseuse for negligence

image.altText: A concrete building is damaged and crumbling after an apparent air attack

props.synopsis: Israel's air force claims the airstrike targeted the commander responsible for an attack on the occupied Golan Heights that left 12 people dead at the weekend.

title.children: IDF strikes Beirut, claims to have killed Hezbollah commander

image.altText: A composite image of Emma McKeown and Regan Smith

props.synopsis: Kaylee McKeown is chasing a third individual Olympic gold but she will need to get past American Regan Smith in the women's 100 metres backstroke final. Follow live.

title.children: McKeown puts Olympic title defence on the line against world-record holder Smith

image.altText: A Rex Airlines plane stands on a runway.

props.synopsis: Rex Airlines, Australia's largest regional and domestic airline operator, enters administration with domestic 737 services grounded and Virgin Australia offering free rebooking.

title.children: Rex Airlines enters voluntary administration but regional routes continuing to operate

image.altText: Sabrina James and Marjorie Johnston share a laugh

props.synopsis: In the midst of a housing crisis, roughly 12 million bedrooms sit empty. But housemates Marjorie Johnston and Sabrina James reckon they have hit on a solution.

title.children: Meet the odd-couple housemates who are 72 years apart

image.altText: A young woman holding a black and white photo of her mother.

props.synopsis: Romany Wake and Shakira Robertson used to be next door neighbours. Now they're trying to support each other after both their mothers were killed tragically in separate incidents.

title.children: 'I've just killed your mum': Romany Wake's father committed murder, then told her to call triple-0

image.altText: Collingwood CEO Craig Kelly.

props.synopsis: The Collingwood Football Club is facing new allegations of racism, with its chief executive officer Craig Kelly accused of making slurs and jokes about Indigenous culture.

title.children: Collingwood Football Club taken to court over racial discrimination allegations

image.altText: Clare Looker appears serious, standing in front of an artwork at a press conference.

props.synopsis: An outbreak of Legionnaires' disease in metropolitan Melbourne has continued to grow, as health authorities race to find the source of infection.

title.children: Melbourne Legionnaires' disease mystery outbreak swells to at least 33

image.altText: A man in sunglasses with tattoos

props.synopsis: A coroner has recommended that Victoria Police look at the viability of having body worn cameras in place for all Special Operations Group (SOG) officers, following an inquest into the death of northern Victoria man Stanley Turvey.

title.children: Coroner says elite police acted within the law when they shot dangerous fugitive Stanley Turvey

image.altText: A woman with blonde hair wearing a dark blazer answers questions from a reporter in a corridor.

props.synopsis: Australian politicians have taken aim at Qantas over the downfall of Rex Airlines but an aviation analysts says the regional carrier itself is to blame.

title.children: Qantas has 'enacted retribution' on Rex Airlines, says Shadow transport minister

image.altText: Primary aged school stduents with school logo green backpacks walk along a city street

props.synopsis: A major school funding agreement is being signed in Darwin, which could bring big changes for every public school in Australia and shape the next decade of schooling.

title.children: The number of teens finishing high school 'is going backwards'. A new funding agreement hopes to solve that

image.altText: A composite image of three young girls, smiling at the camera.

props.synopsis: Taylor Swift pays tribute to the children killed and injured in a stabbing attack at a dance class being held to her music on Monday, saying she's "completely in shock", as the death toll from the incident rises.

title.children: 'Completely in shock': Taylor Swift pays tribute to children killed in UK stabbing attack at dance class as death toll rises

image.altText: Australian players celebrate with their arms in the air

props.synopsis: Australia's men's water polo team take down two-time defending Olympic champions Serbia, backing up their mantra to surprise the world.

title.children: The Aussie Sharks live up to their pledge to 'shock the world' in Paris

image.altText: 7s emotion

props.synopsis: After arriving in Paris as co-favourites for the gold, Australia finishes fourth in the women's rugby sevens after shock losses to Canada and the United States.

title.children: 'They're devastated': Australia misses medals in rugby sevens after US score 85m try at the death

image.altText: Australian basketballer Josh Giddey pushes past two Canada defenders during a men's Olympic basketball match

props.synopsis: Canada has reaffirmed its status as a favourite for a medal in Paris, handing Australia's Boomers their first loss in their second group game.

title.children: Boomers suffer first Olympic defeat after being outmuscled by Canada

image.altText: A doctor gives Hunter a spoonful of puree with peanut powder in it.

props.synopsis: Babies with a peanut allergy will be offered oral immunotherapy in Australia for the first time as part of a new standardised model of care in hospitals across the country.

title.children: Peanut allergies in babies to be treated for the first time under national model of care

image.altText: A sign saying "The Royal Children's Hospital" sits in a garden in front of one of the facility's large, colourful buildings.

props.synopsis: The CEO of Melbourne's Royal Children's Hospital has been told to reapply for her job even though the hospital's board wants to extend her appointment. The government says it is standard practice but doctors disagree.

title.children: Tensions between Victorian government and Royal Children's Hospital board over CEO's future

image.altText: Kamala Harris, in a beige suite, looks over her shoulders at the top of aircraft stairs

props.synopsis: North Carolina Governor Roy Cooper and Michigan Governor Gretchen Whitmer are both out of the race to become Kamala Harris's running mate.

title.children: Kamala Harris running mate race narrows, with two more candidates out

image.altText: A swimmer looks on during a training session

props.synopsis: Lani Pallister, who was regarded as a genuine chance of claiming a medal in the 1,500m freestyle, has withdrawn from the event after testing positive to COVID.

title.children: Lani Pallister withdraws from 1,500m freestyle after testing positive to COVID

image.altText: An aurora visible on the horizon, over water.

props.synopsis: The stunning weather event that delighted stargazers around the world returns to Australian skies, with the geomagnetic storm expected to be at its strongest on Tuesday evening but lasting for several days.

title.children: Aurora australis lights up the sky as BOM forecasts significant geomagnetic activity

image.altText: A woman holds her arm to her forehead while laying on a bed.

props.synopsis: Australian women with menopause are leaving the workforce early over a lack of support, Australian unions tell a Senate inquiry into menopause and perimenopause. They're calling for 10 days paid leave to help keep them at work.

title.children: Australian unions call for 10 days paid reproductive leave to support women with menopause

image.altText: Two female rugby players in Australian colours contest the ball against a rival player.

props.synopsis: Jason Levi and Andrew Goodman are from different states, but they have one very special thing in common — both are watching not one but two of their children representing Australia on the world stage.

title.children: Proud dads of Olympic siblings reflect on the road to Paris

image.altText: An Australian flag flies at the Australian embassy in Jakarta after a bomb attack

props.synopsis: In 2002, Jemaah Islamiah became the most feared terror group in South-East Asia. Now they have publicly renounced violence.

title.children: They were behind the bombings that killed 88 Australians in Bali. Now they've handed over their weapons

image.altText: seine water

props.synopsis: The men's triathlon at the Paris Olympics that was due to take place this afternoon, Australian time, has been postponed because pollution levels in the River Seine remain too high.

title.children: Olympic men's triathlon postponed due to pollution levels in River Seine

image.altText: An aerial shot shows mourners from the Druze minority surrounding five white coffins.

props.synopsis: Israel promised to make Hezbollah pay for the strike in Majdal Shams, but as the war in Gaza drags on it finds itself in a tough position.

title.children: Israel thought two unusual security strategies kept it safe. Here's why they may no longer work

image.altText: A graphic of a hand asking for money.

props.synopsis: Australian businesses are paying untold amounts in ransom to hackers but the government hopes to regain some control with a landmark cybersecurity law.

title.children: Most cyber ransoms are paid in secret but a new law could change that

image.altText: You view an aerial photo of Beirut Airport's three long runways up against a topaz sea and cityscape climbing up nearby hills.

props.synopsis: Flights to and from Beirut are cancelled or delayed and Australians in Lebanon are warned to leave immediately as tensions between Israel and Hezbollah escalate.

title.children: Australians warned not to travel to Lebanon as tensions between Israel and Hezbollah rise

image.altText: Tahiti

props.synopsis: It has broken the record for an Olympic venue being the longest distance away from a host city, and Teahupo'o is providing a spectacular backdrop to one of the newest events at the Games.

title.children: Cruise ship accommodation and the 'pile of skulls' — the Olympics surfing venue is one of the most unique in history

image.altText: Michele Bullock, looking at journalists, wearing a light blazer, standing at a podium, during a press conference

props.synopsis: Ahead of its meeting next week, the RBA has effectively talked itself into a corner: should it come good on its threats of a rate hike if inflation comes in hotter than expected, or will it choose to maintain its apparent reluctance to push rates even higher?

title.children: Why the RBA should hold off on rate hikes

image.altText: Margaret Kelly holds a red mobility scooter amid dirt and debris from housings being pulled down

props.synopsis: Photojournalist Sean Davey captures the crusade to save Port Melbourne's Barak Beacon Estate, and how a community united to highlight the plight of all public housing tenants.

title.children: At 68, Margaret Kelly was told to move from her home. Instead she led a fight for the right to public housing

image.altText: Trump standing in front of a rally of supporters with his fist raised, wearing a blue suit and red MAGA hat

props.synopsis: The FBI says a local police officer took a photo of gunman Thomas Crooks and sent it to other law enforcement officials at the scene of Donald Trump's Pennsylvania rally before the shooting took place.

title.children: US police photographed Trump shooter more than an hour before assassination attempt

image.altText: A crowd dressed in black is gathered at a rally

props.synopsis: Israel and Hezbollah last went to war in 2006, but now, with tensions sky high, all-out war looms again amid the Gaza conflict.

title.children: After 18 years on the fringes, the Middle East's most powerful paramilitary group and its biggest foe now sit on the verge of war

image.altText: a woman in a kitchen in cooking clothes

props.synopsis: A new visa that was quietly introduced last week is already giving hope to migrant workers who are battling for justice against exploitation, a leading legal advocate says.

title.children: 'I followed the rules but I lost my job': Migrant worker welcomes new visa that lets people like her stay in Australia

image.altText: british sea lord

props.synopsis: Britain's visiting naval chief has declared Australia will eventually operate the world's best anti-submarine warfare (ASW) frigates because a closely linked shipbuilding project in the UK is now "stabilising" after suffering damaging initial setbacks.

title.children: British sea lord assures Australian officials troubled warship program 'stabilising'

image.altText: Ariarne Titmus and Mollie O'Callaghan smile for a photo together with their silver and gold medals

props.synopsis: It was Mollie O'Callaghan's night in Paris, but alongside Ariarne Titmus, with the gold medal around her neck and the pressure finally released, she was free to create a moment to live long in Australian Olympic folklore.

title.children: With their rivalry for the ages, O'Callaghan and Titmus have reminded Australia there is so much more to come
